LlaVA [5] is the first vision-language model that is trained on synthetic multimodal language-image instruction-following data generated by language-only GPT-4. 
LlaVA-1.5 [6] further improves it by applying a fully-connected vision-language connector that is stronger than the simpler projector used in LlaVA V1. 
It further explored some open problem, such as scaling to higher resolution inputs, compositional capabilities, and model hallucination, etc. that sheds light on more advanced vision-language model applications.
LlaVA-OneVision, LlaVA-Video, LlaVA-Stronger, LlaVA-ablation, LlaVA-interleave are a series of follow-ups that enhances the performance of the LlaVA model and widens its applications [0][1][2][3][4].
LlaVA-OneVision is the first single model that can simultaneously handle single-image, multi-image, and video scenarios [0];
LlaVA-Video shows that the image-only-trained LLaVA-NeXT model is surprisingly strong on video tasks with zero-shot modality transfer;
LlaVA-Strong demonstrates the LLM model scaling succuss of this cost-efficient strategy [2];
LlaVA-Ablation summarizes the authors' empirical exploration on model architectures and training strategies [3];
LlaVA-Interleave describes the strategies to entend and improve the capability in new scenarios including multi-image, multi-frame, and multi-view, while maintaining the single-image performance.
The latest series of works are introduced in the same paper, where you can conveniently get an overview of the evolution process.
